<H3> <TI>   `Stranded' Arms Transferred to British Plane </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2103113594 Nicosia ALITHIA in Greek 21 Mar 94 pp 1-2 </F>
<F P=103> NC2103113594 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia ALITHIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] The transfer of 28 tons of arms and ammunition 
from the stranded Nigerian plane that has been at Larnaca 
Airport since Tuesday [15 March] to another plane of Tamesis Air 
which arrived by Stansted, England, via Amman, began under 
strict security measures from the airport's police force. 
  The British cargo plane arrived at 1600 yesterday and was 
refueled immediately. The transfer of the arms and ammunition, 
which according to some reports included surface-to-air and 
air-to-air missiles, began two hours later. The Nigerian plane 
was then to depart for Tel Aviv to repair one of its four 
engines, which was the reason it had been stranded at Larnaca 
Airport. [passage omitted] 

