<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   SPD, CSU Criticize Kinkel </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1903174694 Munich SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG in German 19-20 Mar 
94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> AU1903174694 </F>
<F P=104>  Munich SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["mes/ub" report: "Clear Criticism of Kinkel's Crisis </F>
Management"] 
  [Excerpt] Bonn -- The crisis management of FRG Foreign 
Minister Klaus Kinkel (Free Democratic Party of Germany) in the 
affair involving German-French relations has led to a heated 
domestic quarrel. Both the Social Democratic Party of Germany 
[SPD] leadership as well as the Christian Social Union accused 
Kinkel on Friday [18 March] of having overreacted by "summoning" 
French Ambassador Francois Scheer, thus damaging relations 
between Bonn and Paris. Kinkel, on the other hand, said in an 
interview with SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG that German-French relations 
are "of utmost and primary importance." After difficult years 
Bonn and Paris have found a special relationship of a friendly 
nature. This must be preserved at any cost. The German-French 
relationship is of utmost importance for Europe. "I will not 
permit any shadow to fall on that," Kinkel said. 
  Deputy SPD Chairman Oskar Lafontaine -- commissioner for the 
cultivation of German-French cultural relations -- said that the 
tensions that have now erupted between Paris and Bonn have been 
building for some time. Since the fall of the Wall in 1989 the 
Federal Government has made "several serious mistakes" in its 
European policy, he said in an interview with SUEDDEUTSCHE 
ZEITUNG. "We must make efforts to again improve the relationship 
with Paris." As an example Lafontaine cited the fact that in 
1989 Chancellor Helmut Kohl had not coordinated his 10-point 
catalogue on German unification with French President Francois 
Mitterrand. "This was not in the spirit of the German-French 
treaty." 
  Later on, in the policy toward Yugoslavia or regarding 
questions of German financial policy, chancellor and foreign 
minister "did not exercise the necessary restraint and care in 
dealing with France," Lafontaine added. In the future important 
foreign policy decisions must "again be coordinated in the 
spirit of classical diplomacy and partnership." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

