<F P=100> INTER-EURPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   France Urges Europe To Join Pressure on Asian Services </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2103200494 Paris AFP in English 1954 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2103200494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, March 21 (AFP) -- France urged here Monday 
[21 March] that the principle of reciprocity should be strictly 
applied during negotiations to include financial services within 
the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT). 
  In a memorandum given to its European Union [EU] partners 
during a meeting of finance ministers, France said the EU should 
pursue "resolutely offensive" policies in concert with the 
United States. 
  Financial services were excluded from the Uruguay Round GATT 
trade accord wrapped up in Geneva last December, mainly because 
of what the United States judged to be insufficient offers from 
Japan and other Asian countries. 
  Negotiations will resume in 1995. The U.S. authorities, in 
the meanwhile, are following a policy of opening up the American 
market only to financial services from countries offering 
similar access. 
  The French memorandum said the EU should maintain similar 
reciprocal pressure in financial services. If the Union failed 
to do so, it would lose a lever to open up foreign markets and 
lose ground to U.S. competition, it said. 
  "We should use the threat of reciprocity to incite countries 
which have commitments to open up their financial services 
markets to undertake the appropriate reforms and indulge in less 
protectionism," it said. 

</TEXT>

