<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Scharping Rejects Criticism </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2103150394 Munich SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG in German 21 Mar 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> AU2103150394 </F>
<F P=104>  Munich SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["deu" report: "Scharping Calls Criticism `Wretched </F>
Propaganda'"] 
  [Excerpt] Bonn -- The Social Democratic Party [SPD] 
leadership's tax plans if the SPD wins the Bundestag elections 
in October gave rise to a heated debate at the weekend [19-20 
March]. Chancellor Helmut Kohl and other leading representatives 
of the coalition categorically rejected the plan to introduce a 
supplementary tax of 10 percent of the income tax on annual 
salaries of up to 50,000 German marks [DM] for singles and 
DM100,000 for married couples. In contrast, SPD Chairman Rudolf 
Scharping defended the concept. His deputy, Oskar Lafontaine, 
for his part, accused the government of planning further tax 
increases. The government denied this. 
  Scharping rejected criticism of the planned supplementary 
tax 
as "wretched propaganda." Anyone who talks about "destroying 
the readiness to work hard in Germany," is "not quite normal," 
Scharping told SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG. The difference between the 
solidarity surcharge of 7.5 percent of their income tax, which 
is planned by the coalition, and the supplementary tax, is 
small. For a citizen with a monthly gross income of DM8,000 it 
is only DM50. "I think that this is bearable; I do not expect 
enthusiasm but understanding," the SPD chairman said. He said 
that the coalition's claim that higher taxes make people less 
willing to work hard a "completely trite and stupid theory." 
Over the past years the upper income echelons have experienced 
a considerable easing of burdens. If this had significantly 
raised people's willingness to work hard, one should not be in 
the most profound economic crisis since the end of the war now. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

