<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bavaria Sells Stakes in Steel Entreprise, Dasa </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1603143994 Munich SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG in German 16 Mar 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> AU1603143994 </F>
<F P=104>  Munich SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["dm"-signed report: "Bavaria Resigns From Maxhuette and </F>
Dasa"] 
  [Text] Munich -- The Bavarian land government is going to 
resign from the steel industry and the aviation and space 
industry. The land will sell its stakes in the "Neue Maxhuette" 
and the "Lechstahl" enterprise to Max Aicher, a construction and 
steel industrialist of Freilassing. This Cabinet decision was 
announced by Minister President Edmund Stoiber, of the Christian 
Social Union, in Munich on Tuesday [15 March]. "The future of 
the Maxhuette is thus safe," Stoiber said. The looming 
bankruptcy has been avoided, and Sulzbach-Rosenberg will be 
preserved as a steel center and a significant part of jobs in 
Maxhuette will also be saved. However, to attain this 
objective, Bavaria must provide another 140 million German 
marks. Stoiber also announced that in the coming week, the 
Bavarian Government will resign from the German Aviation and 
Space enterprise Dasa. 

</TEXT>

