<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defence Minister Decorates Gen Cot, Praises Effort </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1703191594 Paris AFP in English 1904 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1703191594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, March 17 (AFP) -- French General Jean Cot, 
recalled as commander of UN forces in ex-Yugoslavia after 
outspoken calls for NATO airstrikes in Bosnia, was lauded and 
decorated here Thursday [17 March] by Defence Minister Francois 
Leotard. 
  Leotard presented a visibly moved Cot with the Medal for 
Military Valour and praised the general's "pugnacity and 
determination." 
  Cot, UN Protection Force [UNPROFOR] commander for eight 
months, left office Tuesday -- four months early -- after being 
effectively sacked by UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali 
for surpassing his mandate. 
  The move followed a string of virulent attacks by Cot on UN 
decision-making, including demands late 1993 and early 1994 for 
the right to launch air strikes in Bosnia. 
  Cot also denounced the "humiliations" suffered by UN troops 
prevented by UN rules from properly defending themselves. 
  France over the weekend criticised UN indecision over 
launching reprisals after a series of attacks on French UN 
troops by Bosnian Serb forces in the northwestern Bihac area. 
  Asked Thursday about his future, Cot said he intended to 
"take a month off." 
  Observers noted that at his level -- a five star general -- 
there were few opportunities for advancement in the French Army. 
  If he were to follow the example of General Philippe 
Morillon, the former commander of UN troops in Bosnia, Cot could 
become a government adviser, or could ask for early retirement, 
18 months ahead of the scheduled date. 

</TEXT>

