<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   * Cooperation With Sweden in ASW Studied </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P20523A Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET in Swedish 10 Mar 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> 94P20523A </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Swedish </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Finland Learning Submarine Hunting </F>
in Sweden"] 
  [Text] Finland and Sweden are going to study possibilities 
of establishing closer cooperation regarding signal lights and 
sonar scanning in antisubmarine warfare [ASW]. Joint training is 
also something Finland would like to discuss. 
  Within two weeks a group of Finnish experts -- among them 
Commander Juha Rannikko, chief of the ASW Office on the Naval 
Headquarters Staff -- will go to Sweden in order to discuss with 
their Swedish colleagues what forms of closer cooperation could 
be achieved. 
  Swedish naval sources refused comment on this matter, which 
can be seen as involving a sensitive area. 
  Lieutenant Colonel Soren Trygg of the Swedish Defense 
Staff's 
Naval Command stated in response to a direct question from 
[Swedish news service] FLT that he "is prevented from commenting 
on this," and refused to give any further information on the 
issue. 
  The background to this is that the Finnish and Swedish naval 
chiefs in discussions held in 1992 and 1993 came to agreement on 
studying the possibilities for developing cooperation and 
exchanging experiences "in analysis and operations for passive 
and active sonar systems." 
  Finland would like to have access to the Swedish Navy's 
advanced training simulators, equipment which Finland lacks. 
  "We will first and foremost look at the simulators that the 
Swedish Navy has. We are even considering acquiring similar 
equipment ourselves. Another alternative we discussed is whether 
we could be allowed to train our own operators on the Swedish 
equipment," said Rannikko in a telephone interview with the FLT 
news service. 
  On the other hand, said Rannikko, it is not a question of 
any 
active cooperation between Sweden and Finland in hunting foreign 
submarines. 
  Rannikko refused to comment on how many Finnish military 
personnel would be involved in such possible training in Sweden. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

