<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Norway </F>
<H3> <TI>   Godal, Croatia's Granic Discuss Yugoslav Issues </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2103120794 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1100 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2103120794 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Croatian] Foreign Minister Mate Granic held talks 
with his Norwegian counterpart Bjorn Tore Godal in Oslo today. 
  Minister Granic told reporters that the talks focused on the 
situation in the former Yugoslavia, particularly in the light of 
the latest Washington agreements. He informed the Norwegian 
foreign minister of Croatian activities at the United Nations 
and the Security Council, as well as of perspectives for future 
negotiations with the Bosnian Serbs and the local Serbs in the 
occupied areas in Croatia. 
  The Croatian foreign minister said Norway congratulated 
Croatia on the [Croat-Muslim] agreement as the foundation for 
future peace in Bosnia-Herzegovina. He added that Norway 
believes the problems of the UN-protected areas in Croatia and 
of Bosnia-Herzegovina will have to be solved simultaneously. 
Minister Granic said that Norway is interested in developments 
in the former Yugoslavia and is ready to provide humanitarian 
aid and lend assistance in the reconstruction. Norway will soon 
hold a referendum on joining the EU [European Union], and one of 
Croatia's main aims is to obtain associate membership in the EU, 
Minister Granic said, adding that this will be discussed further. 
  The two ministers will resume talks over a working lunch 
when 
they will discuss mutual relations. An agreement on technical 
and cultural cooperation, which is soon to be signed, is of 
special importance, as well as improved economic relations 
between the two countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

