<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Notes `Identical' Views on Some Confidence Measures </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1803193594 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1745 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1803193594 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Gustave Feissel, the UN secretary general's 
alternate special representative in Cyprus, said that the views 
of the two sides are identical on some of the seven key points 
of the proximity talks agenda on the confidence-building 
measures [CBM's]. In a statement made tonight after meeting 
President Glavkos Kliridhis, Feissel added that other points 
must be further clarified. He said he was satisfied that the 
procedure is progressing well. Feissel added: But, if the two 
sides do not go all the way, what has been achieved so far 
essentially means nothing. 
  Feissel said that with the conclusion of this week's talks, 
which focused on the UN notes, the positions of the two sides 
were determined to a large degree. He said that these positions 
will form the basis of next week's talks. He also said that he 
is convinced that if both sides work toward this goal, an 
agreement on the CBM's can be reached this month. 
  Asked what has been the benefit of the talks so far, Feissel 
said that the form and ways to implement the CBM's on the legal 
regime of UN control of Famagusta and the benefit to the two 
sides from the opening of the fenced-off area and Nicosia 
Airport has been clarified. He added that Joe Clark, the UN 
secretary general's special representative in Cyprus, is 
arriving at a very good time for the talks and aims to help the 
negotiating procedure. 
  Government spokesman Ioannis Kasoulidhis said the Greek 
Cypriot side does not yet have a complete picture of the Turkish 
Cypriot positions. He said the Greek Cypriot side presented its 
positions on Feissel's notes this week. He added that the 
United Nations aims to bring the two sides closer to an 
agreement and stressed that the Greek Cypriot side does not 
reject Feissel's notes on the headlines of the talks agenda. 
  The spokesman concluded that a new round of talks, which 
will 
be more intense than the talks held so far, will be held next 
week with Clark's participation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

