<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia Opposes Consulate General in Kaliningrad </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2103174094 Hamburg DER SPIEGEL in German 21 Mar 93 p 145 </F>
<F P=103> AU2103174094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DER SPIEGEL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Opposition Against Consulate </F>
General"] 
  [Text] Bonn's desire to open a German consulate general as 
soon as possible in Kaliningrad, the former Koenigsberg, meets 
with increasingly determined objections in Moscow. Upon the 
instigation by Foreign Minister Kozyrev, the issue was passed on 
to the Russian Security Council at the beginning of this month. 
Kozyrev recommends putting the Germans off for an indefinite 
period, even if this were to cause the Russians' desired project 
of a consulate general in Frankfurt/Main to fail. He wants to 
talk to his Bonn counterpart, Kinkel, who is visiting Moscow 
this week, in this spirit and warn against a relapse "into the 
Germanic urge to the east": In particular, the debate about 
Koenigsberg, which was started in the European Parliament upon 
the suggestion of German deputies, and the demand for a "special 
relationship" between the European Union and the Kaliningrad 
area are "pure impudence." 

</TEXT>

