<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Troops Withdraw on Schedule </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2203111694 Berlin NEUE ZEIT in German 18 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU2203111694 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin NEUE ZEIT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Withdrawal of Russian Soldiers </F>
According to Schedule"] 
  [Text] Berlin -- The Russian armed forces have so far kept 
to the official schedule for their withdrawal. The government's 
representative for the withdrawal, Major General Hartmut 
Foertsch, announced in Brandenburg on Thursday [17 March] that 
90 percent of the personnel and 88 percent of the vehicles and 
equipment had returned to Russia by the end of March. About 
55,000 members of the military are still deployed in the new 
laender. A total of 250 members of the armed forces have 
applied for asylum in Germany. No decision has yet been made. 
  According to a spokesman for the Berlin Senat, 
Michael-Andreas Butz, Chancellor Helmut Kohl and Russian 
President Boris Yeltsin will participate in the farewell 
ceremony for the Russian troops in August. The Chancellor's 
Office announced that a farewell for the Western Allies will 
also take place in Berlin in September "with high-level 
participation." 
  Butz stated that the talks among the four victorious powers 
have nearly been completed. Agreement has been reached on the 
basic issues. There are plans to organize an outstanding 
farewell ceremony with a tattoo by the Bundeswehr and with the 
participation of the armed forces of the Western Allies. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

