<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Iraq Demands Discussion of Embargo at IPU Conference </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN2103190094 Baghdad INA in Arabic 1820 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> JN2103190094 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad INA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, 21 Mar (INA)--The Iraqi National Assembly 
delegation attending the 91st session of the Interparliamentary 
Union [IPU] inaugurated here today has urged the conferees to 
debate the embargo clamped on Iraq and recommend a lifting of 
the embargo, particularly since Iraq has fulfilled its 
commitments toward the relevant UN Security Council resolutions. 
  The National Assembly delegation headed by Assembly Speaker 
Sa'di Mahdi Salih demanded that this issue be added to the 
agenda of the IPU conference, which was opened by French 
President Francois Mitterrand earlier today. 
  The correspondent of the Iraqi News Agency in Paris said 
that 
the parliamentary delegations attending the conference, 
representing 125 countries, will discuss the Iraqi proposal and 
make a decision on it. 
  The week-long conference will discuss the means of averting 
international conflicts; the United Nations' peacekeeping role; 
protecting the environment; the international political, 
economic, and social situation; and the possible drafting of a 
plan to remedy inequality between men and women in politics. 

</TEXT>

