<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel Meets Gligorov, Supports FYROM Position </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1703180294 Hamburg DPA in German 1719 GMT 17 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1703180294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn -- Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel (Free 
Democratic Party of Germany) received Macedonian [The Former 
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM] President Kiro Gligorov 
today. The two politicians discussed the serious tensions 
between Skopje and Athens, which even exacerbated after the 
imposition of the Greek embargo. Kinkel expressed understanding 
of the attitude of the FYROM not to negotiate under the pressure 
of the Greek embargo, the Foreign Ministry announced after the 
meeting. However, it is important to prevent another increase 
in the tensions and to also show understanding for the Greek 
worries regarding territorial claims against the neighboring 
province of Macedonia "by clarifying the situation." 
  Gligorov, who privately attended a European forum in Bonn 
for 
three days, stressed his readiness for negotiations without any 
preconditions at a news conference on Wednesday [16 March]. 
However, it is out of the question to comply with Greek wishes 
for bilateral talks on the name of Macedonia used on both sides 
of the border, because no results have been achieved in the past 
two years. Now an overall package for this internationally 
recognized FYROM must be presented at the negotiating table, 
Gligorov pointed out. 

</TEXT>

