<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fabbri: Use of Troops in Bosnia `Plausible' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1803091194 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2216 GMT 17 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1803091194 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Bosnia: Deployment of Italian </F>
Troops Possible, Fabbri Says"] 
  [Text] Brussels, 17 Mar (ANSA) -- Italian troops could be 
deployed in Bosnia only once a peace agreement has been reached 
by all warring parties and only in the framework of a NATO 
operation on behalf of the United Nations, Italian Defense 
Minister Fabio Fabbri told the press here Thursday [17 March]. 
  Speaking with the press after his meeting with General 
George 
Joulwan, commander of Atlantic alliance forces in Europe, the 
Italian minister said that, until now, no request has been made 
for the deployment of Italian troops in Bosnia and, were this to 
occur in the future, the decision would be up to the Italian 
Government and parliament. 
  Nevertheless, Fabbri did state that "in the future, I think 
that, with a peace agreement signed by all sides and in the 
framework of a NATO operation to ensure its application, the 
possible use of the Italian military would be, in effect, 
plausible." 
  During today's meeting, Fabbri said General Joulwan voiced 
the gratitude of the Atlantic alliance for the "extraordinary" 
support for operations in the former Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

