<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Andreatta Proposes To Modify EU Institutions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1803114394 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2001 GMT 17 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1803114394 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "European Union: Andreatta Looks </F>
Towards Italy's Duty Presidency"] 
  [Text] Rome, 17 Mar (ANSA) -- Italy will call an 
inter-governmental conference to map out modifications to 
European Union [EU] institutions, to take into account new 
members, when it takes over the European Union rotating 
presidency, for the first half of 1996, Italian Foreign Minister 
Beniamino Andreatta said here on Thursday [17 March]. 
  In an address to the International Affairs Institute, which 
also served as an occasion to review his tenure as Italy's 
diplomatic chief, Andreatta observed how "there is a fundamental 
intolerance towards institutional questions" in European Union 
member states, "even among the original members. When the 
question was raised to prepare for the inter-governmental 
conference to modify the institutions almost no one, except 
Italy, appeared in favor of speeding up the time table." 
  The Italian diplomatic chief went on to add how only now, 
with the conclusion of membership negotiations with Sweden, 
Norway, Finland and Austria, "have we, in a most casual way, 
been able to guide things towards a commitment in Corfu (the EU 
summit ending the Greek duty presidency in June) where 
government chiefs will appoint their permanent representatives 
to the committee which must prepare the inter-governmental 
conference." 
  Andreatta then went on to list some possible alternatives 
for 
institutional change, including "...an Upper House, one of 
government representatives, with a leadership in which some 
Member States, given their size and presence in the EU, become 
permanent members" as well as members "which represent the 
continuity of action." 
  Andreatta's proposal is that of the "hard core" approach 
which has been under discussion for several months, in which 
several states push forward and even go beyond the path set down 
in the Maastricht Treaty on European Union. "At present," the 
foreign minister observed, "the debate on the hard core must 
take into account Britain, which is irreplaceable in Europe." 
  The Italian diplomatic chief went on to recall how some of 
"the most important steps we have taken in the last decade have 
been thanks to Britain. Sometimes Britain's opposition has 
helped the European Community move forward.... I would not like 
the hard core approach to leave out one of the most original and 
important Member States." 
  According to Andreatta, the 1996 inter-governmental 
conference on institutional reform will represent a turning 
point for building a united Europe and "the series of duty 
presidencies, between Germany's and Italy's, will set the pace 
for those which must govern these processes." 
  "But the times are not easy ones to modify and accelerate 
the 
European process" Andreatta concluded, in reference to the 
intolerance to institutional reform "...but occasions like 
these, which could even lead to failure, must be exploited and 
those with more to offer should perhaps try to offer more." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

