<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Trade Ministry Criticizes Japanese Quota </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2103141994 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1820 GMT 19 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2103141994 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "European Union: Italy Critical of </F>
Its Japanese Car Import Quota"] 
  [Text] Rome, 19 Mar (ANSA) -- The 47,000 unit quota for 
Japanese automobile imports to Italy is too high, given the 
overall drop in the demand for new vehicles and the imports of 
the so-called transplants, Japanese cars made in Europe, 
according to a statement issued here Saturday by the Ministry 
for Foreign Trade. 
  According to the ministry, an in-depth review must be made 
of 
the situation which takes into account the various aspects of 
the question. "We are, in fact, even with the individual limits 
for the so-called protected markets, in a situation of a single 
market which allows free circulation among all European 
countries." 
  "Furthermore" the note continued, "the agreement to limit 
`yellow' car imports does not take into account the sale of 
transplants, which account for a significant share of the market 
held by Japanese makes and represents another element of serious 
concern for Italy." 
  The effective performance of the new car market, the 
ministry 
argued, is "in the end influenced by the competitiveness of 
prices, which determined, in 1993, only a partial use of the 
Japanese quota." 
  The statement from the Ministry for Foreign Trade went on to 
underscore how "it is still not clear whether, as in 1993, the 
possibility exists to verify and re-examine, in the course of 
the year, that adjustments which the evolution of the market 
would dictate." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

