<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bank of Italy Issues State Indebtedness Figures </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2103150494 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1111 GMT 21 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2103150494 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "State Debt Nearing </F>
2,000-Trillion-Lire Mark"] 
  [Text] Rome, 21 Mar (ANSA) -- The Bank of Italy's 
supplementary bulletin released today reported that the Italian 
state indebtedness is currently only 190.324 billion lire short 
of hitting the 2,000 trillion lire mark (1.176 trillion dollars). 
  In December 1993, this figure for the first time crashed 
through the 1,800 trillion lire threshold: the exact figure was 
1,809,676 billion lire. 
  With respect to the previous year this was a growth of 10.5 
percent. This meant that the monthly growth in Italy's state 
debt had been something like 14.3 trillion lire. 
  Furthermore, these figures include the accumulated 
indebtedness of the central administration only and exclude 
local administrations and public agencies now transformed into 
joint stock companies. 
  Should these be included in the calculation as well, a much 
more complicated matter, the total public indebtedness could be 
ascertained only up to October of last year when it was 
estimated to be 1,815,692 billion lire (that same month the 
total state debt was 1,770,966 billion lire). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

