<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Outstanding Loans Increased in 1993 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2103151094 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1318 GMT 21 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2103151094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Outstanding Bank Debts Rise Sharply"] </F>
  [Text] Rome, 21 Mar (ANSA) -- The outstanding loans or bad 
debts held by Italian credit institutions continues to rise 
sharply and at the end of last year totaled in the neighborhood 
of 70 trillion lire, over 41.5 billion dollars, sector sources 
confirmed here Monday [21 March]. 
  The outstanding debts included over 46 trillion lire in 
expired loans together with 23 trillion in bad debts held by 
special credit institutes. 
  Outstanding medium-to-long-term loans held by special credit 
institutes jumped 13.9 percent in December, over the previous 
month, and 34.1 percent on a 12-month basis. 
  Short-term bad debts, however, for the first time declined, 
dipping from 47.029 trillion lire in November to 46.335 trillion 
lire at the end of last year, for a reduction of 1.4 percent. 
Outstanding short-term debts, however, rose 23.7 percent in 
December compared to the same month in 1992. 

</TEXT>

