<H3> <TI>   Andreatta Warns Against `Radical Shift' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1803134094 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1737 GMT 17 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1803134094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Andreatta Warns Against Political </F>
Extremes"] 
  [Text] Rome, 17 Mar (ANSA) -- Italian Foreign Minister 
Beniamino Andreatta on Thursday [17 March] lashed out against 
any radical shift in Italy, Left or Right, and stressed how any 
radical position would be of no use to the nation's foreign 
policy. 
  In an address to the International Affairs Institute, which 
represented an overview of his tenure as Italy's diplomatic 
chief, Andreatta warned against those "who want to confine 
foreign policy inside a geo-political reality, like the Italian 
Right would appear to, which in some way abandons its 
(traditional) openness." 
  Andreatta went on to voice his opposition to those who call 
for the re-organization of the Foreign Ministry. "I know very 
well what needs to be reformed, but I am skeptical towards those 
positions which claim to be novel. It is my opinion that 
Italian society needs a more adequate foreign policy, but based 
on traditional lines." 
  The foreign minister, a trained economist, then argued how, 
at least based on the pre-election statements, radical shifts in 
either direction would offer no "useful solutions for the 
nation's economic problems." 
  The foreign policy platforms of the various forces running 
for the March 27-28 elections were also reviewed by Andreatta in 
an article published by the magazine IL REGNO, with the foreign 
minister observing "What is essential is the interest a nation 
shows towards playing a leading role on an international level. 
Very often, our country, even those people who are culturally 
sophisticated, when faced with an international dilemma waiver 
between a crude vision of the balance of power or a disarmed 
vision which does not appear to understand the plurality of 
views, the interests on which the community of nations is based." 

</TEXT>

