<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks Adjourned to 26 Mar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2203171494 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 1705 GMT 22 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2203171494 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Geoff Meade, PRESS ASSOCIATION, Brussels] </F>
  [Text] European foreign ministers today failed to breach 
the log-jam over voting rights which has brought turmoil to 
plans to enlarge the Union and left Britain all but isolated. 
  The talks in Brussels were adjourned until Saturday [26 
March] when the 12 foreign ministers, including Britain's 
Douglas Hurd, will meet in Ioannina, Greece, in a renewed bid to 
heal the rift. 
  But today, Mr Hurd emerged from the meeting insisting that 
the talks had not collapsed and that Britain remained "at the 
heart of Europe." 
  The crisis hinges on the number of votes needed to block 
European decisions once the European Union [EU] is enlarged from 
12 to 16 next January with the addition of Sweden, Norway, 
Finland and Austria. 
  The refusal by Britain and Spain to adapt the voting rules 
has triggered the current stand-off which leaves Britain 
ominously isolated and has become a major distraction for the 
Conservative Party in the run up to Euro elections in June. 
  At present EU nations have to muster a total of 23 votes out 
of the 76 available to block a contentious proposal which means 
at least three of the 12 member states must vote together 
against any proposition. 
  The new proposals increase the total votes to 90 with the 
four new members and seek to raise the number needed for a veto 
to 27. 
  Mr Hurd had arrived in Brussels saying he was not seeking to 
"torpedo" enlargement plans but would not be "hustled" into any 
agreement which was not in British interests. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

