<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministers on Failure of EU Enlargement Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Belgium's Claes Says EU `Losing Credibility' </H4>
<F P=102> LD2203182994 Brussels La Une Radio Network in French 1700 
GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2203182994 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels La Une Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Earlier this month Austria, Sweden, Finland, and 
Norway -- the latter with some delay -- decided to join the 
European Union [EU]. But this enlargement of the Europe of 12 to 
the Europe of 16 requires a reform of the institutions of the 
Union. In addition, the future of the blocking minority in 
decisionmaking will have to be determined. [passage omitted] 
Jean-Michel Mostart has met Belgian Foreign Minister Willy 
Claes, who doubts the entry of the four nations in the Union on 
1 January 1995 will take place as scheduled. Willy Claes thinks 
Europe is losing its credibility: 
  [Begin Claes recording] We are losing some of our 
credibility, externally and internally. Last Friday I was in 
Washington. There I met colleagues who belong to governments 
that are candidates for membership. They said to me that they 
failed to understand any of our talks, and, above all, the 
opponents of the European Community in their countries will take 
advantage and launch a likely successful campaign. This is the 
external aspect. As for the internal aspect, I would like to 
see some parliaments looking again into their position vis-a-vis 
this European construction. Once again, I have the feeling that 
this is not just a detail, but a discussion on principles that 
are the basis of the fundamental orientation of Europe of the 
future. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

