<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Athens Welcomes State Department Notice on FYROM </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2203205794 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1800 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2203205794 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Athens considers the latest U.S. Government moves 
as a good omen for the U.S. stance on the issue of The Former 
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia [FYROM]. Following the 
appointment of a special coordinator, the State Department 
issued a notice enforcing the use of The Former Yugoslav 
Republic of Macedonia for Skopje. Foivos Karzis has the 
following report: 
  [Begin Foivos Karsis recording] The State Department notice 
actually prohibits its officials from mentioning Skopje using 
the name of Macedonia under the pretext of brevity or 
simplification. The Greek Government is obviously satisfied with 
this development, since it sees this as a continuation of a 
positive climate that prevails in Washington, such as the 
appointment of Mr. Matthew Nimetz as the State Department's 
special envoy. [end recording] 
  Deputy Foreign Minister Yeoryios Papandreou also made a 
statement on the importance of the State Department notice to 
our correspondent Nina Asimakopoulou. 
  [Begin recording] [Papandreou] The significance is that our 
country's sensitivity toward this problem is recognized in the 
most official way by the United States. If one combines this 
with President Clinton's latest announcement that he would not 
establish diplomatic relations with the FYROM until Prime 
Minister Andreas Papandreou visits the United States, and with 
the announcement that Mr. Nimetz has been appointed U.S. special 
envoy, then we can see the U.S. political will to contribute 
positively toward the efforts for a just solution to this 
problem. 
  [Asimakopoulou] Do you believe that the Greek Government's 
measures have brought about results? 
  [Papandreou] I believe that they have received the message 
that Greece considers this issue a very serious one, as we have 
been indicating for months during our contacts and discussions. 
This has been achieved not only by the Greek Government, but 
citizens of the United States have also played a significant 
role. [end recording] 
  The government spokesman also described the U.S. State 
Department decision as positive and noted that similar 
developments also took place in Australia, where the government 
decided that, until the dispute over the Skopje name is 
resolved, the Skopjeans will be officially called 
Slavomacedonians. 
  These moves by Washington also show a clear [word 
indistinct] 
of the climate that the U.S. Government desires to formulate in 
view of the prime minister's upcoming visit to the White House. 
Deputy Foreign Minister Yeoryios Papandreou will leave for the 
United States tomorrow to prepare for the prime minister's 
visit. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-19871 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu056_p_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-056 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU's Delors Sends Papandreou Letter on FYROM </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2303091494 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 0500 GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2303091494 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] European Union [EU] Commissioner Jacques Delors has 
sent another letter to Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou asking 
the Greek Government to raise the issue of the embargo against 
The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia [FYROM] at the EU 
Council of Ministers. According to Community observers, this 
request indicates that the possibility of referring Greece to 
the European Court has lost momentum. Correspondent Mairi Savva 
reports from Brussels: 
  [Savva] EU Commission President Jacques Delors has sent 
another letter to Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou regarding 
the FYROM. In his letter, Delors asks the Greek Government to 
raise the issue of the economic embargo at the EU Council of 
Foreign Ministers. Political observers in Brussels view this 
move as another goodwill gesture from the Commission, which 
right now does not want to lodge a complaint against Greece at 
the European Court. 
  After the extraordinary Council of Ministers meeting ended, 
Delors and Theodhoros Pangalos, the alternate foreign affairs 
minister and EU president, gave a joint news conference. 
Unfortunately, no agreement was reached on the major political 
issue of how to make decisions after the EU expands. The 
Commission and 10 member states favor an arithmetical adjustment 
when decisions are made, with a special majority so as not to 
make decisionmaking any more difficult. Britain and Spain have 
strongly protested; and the European Parliament now may not 
ratify the expansion if this is done according to the solution 
proposed by these two countries. The issue will be discussed 
next weekend during the informal EU Foreign Ministers meetings 
in Ioannina, which will not deal exclusively with the great 
political problems that concern the EU, such as the former 
Yugoslavia and the situation in the Middle East. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

