<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Decision To Send Turkish Troops to Bosnia Protested </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2203223194 Athens ET-1 Television Network in Greek 2130 
GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2203223194 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ET-1 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Foivos Karzis] </F>
  [Text] UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali's decision 
to suggest to the Security Council the dispatch of Turkish blue 
helmets to Bosnia has caused an immediate and strong reaction 
from Athens. Categorical opposition was expressed in a letter 
that Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias addressed urgently a 
short time ago to Security Council President French delegate 
Jean-Bernard Merimee. 
  The letter points out the need for the United Nations to 
observe the principle that rules out the participation in peace 
forces of bordering states or countries that have historic links 
to any of the parties involved in a conflict. 
  Mr. Papoulias is now chairing a conference being attended by 
top officials of the Foreign Ministry. 
  Earlier, UN spokesman Joe Sills said that Butrus-Ghali had 
decided to suggest to the Security Council that Turkey be added 
to the list of states that are authorized to contribute men to 
the UN peace force in the former Yugoslavia. The spokesman also 
noted that Butrus-Ghali decided to suggest the relaxation of the 
criteria prohibiting certain states from participating in the 
peace forces by invoking the recent developments in Bosnia and 
the need not to lose the current international momentum because 
the UN cannot muster enough forces. Mr. Sills avoided giving a 
direct answer on why Butrus-Ghali suggested the dispatch of blue 
helmets only from Turkey and not from other countries that have 
also offered, such as Italy and Greece. However, he did not 
rule out the possibility that there might be a similar 
suggestion in the immediate future. 
  Thorvald Stoltenberg, the UN mediator on the former 
Yugoslavia, confirmed that Mr. Merimee and representatives of 
other Security Council permanent members are maintaining a 
positive stance on the possibility of dispatching Turkish blue 
helmets. According to ATHENS NEWS AGENCY reports, UN circles 
believe that it is possible that approval will come in the next 
few days for the dispatch of 1,000 Turkish troops who, it is 
assumed, will be deployed primarily in the Croatian areas of 
Bosnia and certainly away from areas controlled by the Serbs. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-19887 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu056_q_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-056 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Envoy: Troops Will Act `Responsibly' in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2303073794 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 0700 
GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2303073794 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Recorded statement by Ambassador Inal Batu, permanent </F>
representative to the United Nations] 
  [Text] UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali today 
finally reached the decision we have been waiting for. He has 
decided to recommend to the UN Security Council that it approve 
Turkey's proposal to send troops to UNPROFOR, [UN Protection 
Forces] the peace force in former Yugoslavia. 
  Naturally, this is a satisfactory development for us. We 
have always claimed the following: UN officials themselves have 
been stating that there is a shortage of troops in that region. 
We, in turn, have proposed sending a force with the aim of 
contributing to peace. Our proposal is now deemed appropriate. 
We believe that the UN Security Council endorsement of the UN 
secretary general's recommendation is a mere formality. We do 
not foresee any difficulties in this regard. 
  This is not the first time Turkey has participated in UN 
peace forces. The Turkish Armed Forces have served with 
disciple, self-sacrifice, and honor in all previous UN 
operations. Those who doubt that the same sense of 
responsibility will prevail in former Yugoslavia as well are 
mistaken and prejudiced. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>
